**Note** 

If you need to work with `Date` objects, you can

    dateObject.toInstant();

https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Date.html#toInstant--

This example uses Instant.now() so it is easy to test. If you uncomment line with the `Thread.sleep()` you will see the dates that are printed out will be the same even though the sleep would have caused the dates to be different.

Do you realize that `java.util.Date` objects are always in UTC? So you won&#39;t be trading time-of-day in Montr&#233;al or Kolkata. If UTC is what you want, read on, else edit your Question.

Avoid the troublesome old legacy date-time classes, now supplanted by the java.time classes. The `java.util.Date` class is replaced by `Instant` as a point on the timeline in UTC.

    Instant instantNew = newUtilDate.toInstant();
    Instant instantOld = oldUtilDate.toInstant();

Convert to `OffsetDateTime` objects to enable working with parts. 

    OffsetDateTime odtNew = instantNew.atOffset( ZoneOffset.UTC );
    OffsetDateTime odtOld = instantOld.atOffset( ZoneOffset.UTC );

Now you can extract the date portion or the time-of-day portion and intermix.

    LocalDate ld = odtNew.toLocalDate() ;
    LocalTime lt = odtOld.toLocalTime() ;
    OffsetDateTime odtMix = OffsetDateTime.of( ld , lt , ZoneOffset.UTC );

Best to avoid the legacy classes. But if you really need a `java.util.Date` as your result, extract an `Instant` and convert.

    java.util.Date d = java.util.Date.from( odtMix.toInstant() );

