The problem is that when you remove a node at index `i`, the next node (that had index `i+1`) will be at that index `i`, but still your loop increases `i`, which means that this &quot;next&quot; node will never be inspected.

In practice this means that if you have two *consecutive* nodes that have a value greater than 25, only the first of these two will be removed.

There are many ways to solve this, but a quick fix is to have `i` start at the end and have it move towards the beginning (to 0):

```
for (int i = list.size() - 1; i &gt;= 0; i--) {
  if ((int) list.get(i) &gt; 25) {
    list.remove(i);
  }
}
```

Now it will produce the expected results. 

Still, this algorithm is not very efficient, since `.get(i)` will have to iterate the list each time from the start, giving this algorithm a time complexity of O(&#119899;&#178;). This is not optimal.

Better is to write a function that will iterate **once** through the list and will remove nodes (with a certain condition) *during* that single traversal. Then you&#39;ll have a time complexity of O(&#119899;).

